  "text": "The small optomechanical coupling rate is mostly attributed to the large optical cavity mode volume and the small mode overlap between the optical and the SAW modes. The optoelastic coupling is inversely proportional to the cavity length, g 0 ∝ 1/L, where L is the length of the optical cavity. If a commercially available LiNbO 3 substrate with the thickness of 100 µm is used along with a fiber-optical cavity construction [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] with its cavity length of 300 µm, the optomechanical coupling rate of the order of 10 Hz could be achieved. This coupling rate is comparable to that of the membrane-in-themiddle-type microwave-optical transducer whose conversion efficiency is nearly 10% [CITATION_3] . While their transducer suffers from residual thermal phonons at 4 K because of the low mechanical frequency of the membrane, our transducer based on the high-frequency SAW, 100 times higher than in the membrane, could be cooled to the quantum ground state in the environment at 40 mK. In addition, the rigid solid-state SAW device along with the fiber-based cavity would make the system more robust in the cryogenic environment. The system's cooperativity defined by C = 4ng 2 0 /γκ, where n indicates intracavity photon numbers, κ and γ are decay rates of the optical cavity and the SAW resonator, respectively, would be increased up to C ≃ 1 after the modification described above, assuming the optical input power of 10 mW and the mechanical Q-factor of 10 5 , which we observe with a conventional planar SAW resonator on LiNbO 3 substrate. In this regime, optomechanical control of the SAW resonator mode such as laser cooling would be possible.",
